subSubSection.paragraph:
Pronotum
: Transverse, wider than long, distinctly narrower than elytra width, making the habitus of sub-pholeuonoid aspect (
Fig.1
). Lateral edge in dorsal observation (
Figs. 2, 3
) slightly sinuate concave, bell-like form, maximum width on posterior edge. Dorsal face strongly pubescent, with uniform distribution of short semierect setae.

Thorax:
Mesocoxal cavities separated by a keel, not confluent. Mesosternal keel (carena mesosternale) well developed, elevated and flattened, lanceolate, posteriorly reduced and thickened, extended to the posterior edge of coxal cavities (
Figs. 7, 9
). In lateral view keel is elevated with ventral edge straight, not dentate and entire from thorax colum to the posterior edge of mesocoxal cavities (
Fig. 9
). Mesosternal intercoxal apophysis bifid, short and narrow, equally long as wide (
Fig. 7
). Suture between mesosetrnum and mesepisternum is partly atrophied on its anterior side, not extending to the colum (
Fig. 7
). Metendosternite (furca or Crowson’s organ) “V” shaped with dorsal arms twice as long as stalk (
Fig. 24
). Metatergal apparatus with medial longitudinal groove (posterior process) strongly reduced, rudimentary and oversized by scutellum posterior beak (
Fig. 21
). Scutellum triangular, wide than long, mostly glabrous.

Male genitalia
: Aedeagus 
0.64–0.65 mm
long, broad and truncate with median lobe more or less equally wide all of its length in dorsal view (
Fig. 25
). In lateral view (
Fig. 26
) median lobe tubular and strongly curved in the middle and with sharply deflexed apex. Internal sac of aedeagus without strong sclerotized structures only on its medio apical side; some weakly sclerotized or partly hyaline structures visible. No basal “Y” sclerotized structure present. Basal lamina of median lobe wide and basally invaginated backwards. Ventral lamina of tegmen parallel with median lobe and extended along basal lamina. Parameres (lateral styles) straight, mostly evenly wide all its length, parallel with median lobe, shorter than median lobe, with two apical long setae and one subapical (interno-lateral) short seta (
Figs. 25, 26
). Paramere apex with small terminal hyaline membranous appendage. Male genital segment (IX sternite, urosternite) in lateral view reduced to a chitinous ring. In dorsal view (
Fig. 27
) with prolonged, rounded ventral lobe and small prolonged process on posterior side of its sternal part and with prolonged narrow lateral stylets on its tergal part.
